HEADWORD: Flay
<hw>Flay</hw> <pr>(fl⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Flayed</conjf> <pr>(fl⟦amac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Flaying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>flean</ets>, <ets>flan</ets>, AS. <ets>fle⟦aacute⟧n</ets>; akin to
D. <ets>vlaen</ets>, Icel. <ets>fl⟦amac⟧</ets>, Sw.
<ets>fl⟦aring⟧</ets>, Dan. <ets>flaae</ets>, cf. Lith.
<ets>pleszti</ets> to tear, <ets>plyszti</ets>, v.i., to burst, tear;
perh. akin to E. <ets>flag</ets> a flat stone, <ets>flaw</ets>.]</ety>
<def>To skin; to strip off the skin or surface of; <as>as, to
<ex>flay</ex> an ox; to <ex>flay</ex> the green earth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With her nails⟦br⟧
